The nonlinear load model is used to simulate both voltage and current harmonic distortion. The nonlinear model involves a three-phase universal bridge diode connected across the series inductive-resistive branch. The three-phase universal bridge has a snubber resistance R = 9 Ω, infinite snubber capacitance, internal resistance (Ron) = 2e-2 Ω, internal inductance (Lon) = 0, and forward voltage = 0 V. The series inductive resistive load across the universal bridge consists of 1 mH inductance and 5 Ω resistance. This nonlinear load is connected after the NRR 11 KV/400 V left transformer, and readings are taken at the LTS left busbar for a duration of 0.2 to 0.4 s. Figure 7 shows the different performances corresponding to the NRR network simulation by adding the three-phase nonlinear model. It is evident that from 0.2 to 0.4 s, the power factor decreases to 0.9363 as shown in Fig. 7d, and both \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
